The paper discusses an experimental study on attackers logged on a compromised machine, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The study involves a high interaction honeypot, which is a network security tool used to lure attackers into a trap, and thus, the paper may also belong to the network and internet security (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the lessons learned from the deployment of the honeypot, which may fall under the software engineering (cs.SE) and systems and control (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper mentions the use of a distributed system of low-interaction honeypots, which may fall under the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category.
